12.body:
jq is a JSON parser. All examples are run on this object which will be referred to as json. { "firstName": "John", "lastName": "Smith", "isAlive": true, "age": 27, "address": { "streetAddress": "21 2nd Street", "city": "New York", "state": "NY", "postalCode": "10021-3100" }, "phoneNumbers": [ { "type": "home", "number": "212 555-1234" }, { "type": "office", "number": "646 555-4567" } ], "children": [], "spouse": null
}
12.title: jq

13.body:
# firstName
jq '.firstName' json ## "John" # age
jq '.age' json ## 27
13.breadcrumbs: Shell » Utils » jq » Extract a top-level field
13.title: Extract a top-level field

14.body:
Get all fields of the address object jq '.address' json ## {
## "streetAddress": "21 2nd Street",
## "city": "New York",
## "state": "NY",
## "postalCode": "10021-3100"
## } [] for output without object keys jq '.address[]' json -r # raw output wihout quotes ## 21 2nd Street
## New York
## NY
## 10021-3100 Single key jq '.address.streetAddress' json ## "21 2nd Street"
14.breadcrumbs: Shell » Utils » jq » Extracting lower level fields
14.title: Extracting lower level fields

15.body:
jq '.firstName,.lastName' json ## "John"
## "Smith" The default behaviour is to print each filed on a new line. To get them on the same line, use + to concatenate the fields. This operator can be used to add other strings like spaces and punctuation. jq '.firstName + .lastName' json ## "JohnSmith" jq '.firstName + " " + .lastName' json ## "John Smith" jq '.lastName+ ", " + .firstName ' json ## "Smith, John "
15.breadcrumbs: Shell » Utils » jq » Extract multiple fields
15.title: Extract multiple fields

16.body: To get multiple fields under the same object, use .object | .key to get the values. jq -r '.address | .city + ", " + .state' json ## New York, NY
16.breadcrumbs: Shell » Utils » jq » Extract multiple fields hierarchically
16.title: Extract multiple fields hierarchically

17.body:
Lists can be indexed during retrieval. Objects cannot be indexed with numbers. Empty [] retrieves all elements jq -r '.phoneNumbers[]' json ## {
## "type": "home",
## "number": "212 555-1234"
## }
## {
## "type": "office",
## "number": "646 555-4567"
## } Indexing jq '.phoneNumbers[0].type' json ## "home" jq '.phoneNumbers[0,1].type' json ## "home"
## "office" Retrieve all elements of a list jq '.phoneNumbers[] | .type' json ## "home"
## "office" All elements with formatting jq -r '.phoneNumbers[] | .type + ": " + .number' json ## home: 212 555-1234
## office: 646 555-4567
17.title: Lists

19.body:
xdotool getactivewindow getwindowgeometry gets the active window geometry Window 56623115 Position: 2297,22 (screen: 0) Geometry: 1143x1386 and adding the --shell flag returns the output as machine readable. WINDOW=56623115
X=2297
Y=22
WIDTH=1143
HEIGHT=1386
SCREEN=0 Running this with eval stores each geometry value as a shell variable. This can be put into a script using bc to calculate the center position: eval $(xdotool getactivewindow getwindowgeometry --shell)
xdotool mousemove -w $WINDOW $(echo $WIDTH/2 | bc) $(echo $HEIGHT/2 | bc)

22.body: notify-send needs the DBUS session address to display the notification. This job shows a notification every minute after getting the DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS: */1 * * * * eval "export $(egrep -z DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS /proc/$(pgrep -u $LOGNAME gdm-x-session)/environ)"; notify-send "hello world"
22.title: Sending notifications

25.body: Run: git --log --oneline --decorate --all $( git fsck --no-reflog | awk '/dangling commit/ {print $3}' ) Look for an entry in the log starting with WIP whose diff matches the lost stash, copy its has and run git stash apply [hash] The hash can also be found using the gitk gui: gitk --all $( git fsck --no-reflog | awk '/dangling commit/ {print $3}' ) This will open a gitk window with a log. From https://stackoverflow.com/a/91795 .

25.title: Restoring a lost stash

28.body:
To change discrete axis labels in a ggplot, get the labels from the dataset or make a custom list. # pull label vector from dataframe
custom_labels <- df$label_col %>% unique() %>% # into other functions df %>% ggplot(aes(...)) + ... scale_x_discrete(labels = custom_labels) # or for simple regex df %>% ggplot(aes(...)) + ... scale_x_discrete(labels = function(x) { sub("pattern", "replacement", x) })

28.title: Change axis label elements from dataset

29.body: ggplot(df, aes(...) +... scale_x_discrete(labels = function(x) { sub("\\s", "\n", x) })

30.body:
The patchwork library can make panels with plots. The tag from the plot is used as the figure label in the panel. Layouts can be controlled with + for horizontal arrangement and / for vertical arrangement. These operators can be used with parentheses to control precedence. library(patchwork)
plot1 <- ggplot(...) + geom_...() + labs(tag = "A")
plot2 <- ggplot(...) + geom_...() + labs(tag = "B")
plot3 <- ggplot(...) + geom_...() + labs(tag = "C") # A B C plot1 + plot2 + plot3 # A B
# C plot1 + (plot2 / plot3)
30.title: Patchwork

4.body: The default bindings are those found in the emacs editor and use Control and Alt as modifiers to send commands.
4.title: Emacs bindings

5.body: C : control M : Meta or Alt C-a: move to beginning of line C-e: move to end of line C-f: move forward one character C-b: move backward one character M-f: move forward one word M-b: move backward one word
5.title: Navigation

6.body: C-h: delete one character back C-d: delete one character forward C-k: delete everything in front of cursor C-w: delete one word backwards M-d: delete one word forwards C-u: clear line C-l: clear screen (not including current line)
6.title: Deletion

8.body: C-p: move up in history C-n: move down in history C-r: search backward in history (best with fzf) C-s: search forward in history
8.title: History

9.body: Adding set -o vi in .bashrcor inputrc sets vim keybindings in the shell and other shell based interfaces like the python REPL. For zsh use bindkey -v. An indicator of the current mode can be shown in bash >= 4.4. In normal mode, typing v opens the current shell input in vim. The default escape key or sequence can be changed using bind or bindkey. On the Colemak layout I use ',m'. # bash bind '",m":"\e"' # zsh bindkey -e ,m \\e
9.title: Vim bindings
